 built between 379 and 383 A.D. by these three emperors (CIL vi. 1184), as the monumental
end of their PORTICUS MAXIMAE (q.v.). It stood close to the pons Aelius,
and probably spanned its southern approach. It was destroyed in the
fourteenth century, but some traces of it were visible in the sixteenth
(Eins. 2. 2; 8. 2 (per arcum); Mirab. 5; Ordo Ben. ap. Jord. ii. 665;
HJ 598; BC 1893, 20; Lib. Cens. Fabre-Duchesne, ii. 154).

 The arcus Formae mentioned in the Ordo Benedicti (Jord. ii. 665;
Lib. Cens. Fabre-Duchesne ii. 154; HCh 258-259) is no doubt the ARCUS
IOHANNIS BASILII (q.v.).

