The name Aventinus is still unexplained, in spite of the many etymologies offered by Roman antiquarians (Varro, LL v. 45; Liv. i. 3. 9;
Fest. 19; Verg. Aen. vii. 657, and Servius, ad loc.; Lydus, de mag. i. 34;
Jord. i. 1. 180-183; HJ 151-153; Merlin, op. cit. 26-36). The suggestion
that the word represents an ancient Italian, or perhaps Ligurian, settlement may possibly find some support in the use of PAGUS AVENTINENSIS
(q.v.). The statement of Festus (148: Murciae deae sacellum  erat
sub monte Aventino qui antea Murcus vocabatur) is probably false.

